  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing access to improved water, sanitation and hygiene services in Tanzania</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Concern Tanzania&#x2019;s WASH activities will reach 128,625 beneficiaries in 2015. In line with the approved Exit Strategy activities focused on construction and infrastructure will come to an end in the first quarter of 2015. This will facilitate an increased focus on sustainability of hardware interventions by working with community-based Water User Groups. Concern in partnership with Community-based Health Care Council (CBHCC) and Tanzania Water and Environmental Sanitation (TWESA) will continue to implement the sustainable access to water project in Ngara and Biharamulo districts in Kagera region and Kibondo district in Kigoma region, in Western Tanzania. Building on previous construction activities, the project seeks to facilitate and support the empowerment of poor and vulnerable communities to own and manage water sources for ensuring sustainable and equitable access to clean and safe water, preventing waterborne diseases and establishing resilient livelihoods that can cope with shocks and disasters and adapt to climate change.</narrative>
  </description>
